‘The sea belongs to us’: landlocked Bolivia hopes court reopens Pacific route
Sailors guard a naval headquarters in La Paz.
In public buildings they wave navy blue flags.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, naval bases display the motto: "The sea belongs to us by right,
Getting it back is a duty.”
All over Bolivia, a land without a sea, they still vividly remember the coast lost to Chile in a bloody conflict over resources that took place in the 19th century, in addition to the longing to sail again through the Pacific Ocean.
These hopes may be the highest in decades, as Bolivia awaits a ruling from the International Court of Justice by October 1, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the drive, a spirit of unity and serenity and, of course, is waiting for the result with a positive vision,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will watch the International Court of Justice ruling on large screens scattered across the country, hoping that the Hague court will rule in favor of Bolivia’s claim that, after decades of intermittent talks, Chile has an obligation to negotiate to grant Bolivia a sovereign outlet to the sea.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president, who is waging a controversial re-election battle next year, also has a lot to say about Monday’s resolution.
“We are very close to returning to the Pacific Ocean,” he promised at the end of August.
However, some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to rule in favor of Bolivia and that the situation would change little if it did so.
The Netherlands-based U.N. body has no power to adjudicate Chilean territory and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of potential talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice’s ruling comes just six months after the closing arguments indicates that the case “was not complicated,” said Paz Zárate, a Chilean expert in international law.
Far from promoting Bolivia’s cause, the past four years may have hindered it.
“The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” Zárate said.
He further suggested that Morales’ belligerent rhetoric has undermined any residual Chilean goodwill.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to talk at some point, but it will be extremely difficult to hold talks after this.
The two countries have not exchanged ambassadors since 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodríguez Veltzé, Bolivia’s representative in The Hague, rejected the idea that the court’s decision-making was unusually swift.
On Monday, Bolivia will be offered “an extraordinary opportunity to open a new era of relations with Chile” and the possibility of “putting an end to 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits,” he said.
Likewise, Calzadilla denied that Morales, who is still one of the most popular presidents in Latin America, used the maritime issue as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right to have access to the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
“The resolution is an opportunity to see that we have to leave the past behind.”
