John Edward: Language skills are fundamental for the citizens of the world
Scotland’s independent schools have a track record of academic excellence that has continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding test scores that is bolstered by individual and collective successes in the fields of sport, art, music and other community projects.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these centres, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to deliver the best level of service to pupils and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students to continue their studies of higher education, for the career they choose and for the place they occupy as citizens of the world.
As an educational sector that can design and implement an adapted curriculum, it is observed that modern languages remain a popular and desired subject in schools.
As Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message comes to his head.
If you speak to him in his tongue, it reaches his heart.”
This is a powerful reminder that if you want to build relationships and build trust with people in other countries, you can’t rely on English alone.
If we take into account the recent results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the ranking tables, with the highest pass rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages obtained an A, the highest grade.
The data, collected from the 74 schools that are part of the SCIS, showed that 72% of students obtained an A in Mandarin, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish also obtained an A.
This shows that Scotland’s independent schools support foreign languages as a fundamental competence that both children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, it is considered that, as a subject, languages are at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of independent schools and everywhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK’s Employment and Skills Commission found that, of the reasons employers gave for the difficulties they encountered in filling jobs, 17% were attributed to a shortage of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly indispensable to prepare young people for their future careers.
Potential job opportunities that require languages are on the rise, so these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career that someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future thanks to a competition like this, which will last a lifetime.
Being able to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically allow that person to get ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% of them did not speak a foreign language well enough to carry on a conversation, and the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage, 15%, was French.
For this reason, investing in language teaching is now important for today’s children.
If they know several languages, especially those of developing economies, children will be equipped to have better opportunities to find quality employment.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Some centres will focus on the most classic modern languages, while others will teach the languages considered most important for the UK by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever the interests of a child, in independent schools you can always choose between several languages taught by teaching staff specialized in this subject.
Independent schools in Scotland devote all their efforts to providing a learning environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills needed to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At the moment, it is undeniable that, in a global business environment, languages continue to be of vital importance for the future of the country, so this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should be considered "competences for international communication".
Independent schools will continue to offer these options, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
I wish he would do well.
John Edward is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Colleges.
