The study, conducted by the National Trust for Scotland, will follow common bats and sopranos, as well as riverine Daubenton and long-eared brown bats from Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed at strategic locations on the property to track the bats’ activities during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations with portable detectors.
Experts will analyze the sounds picked up in the recordings to find out how often bats call and what species do it.
A habitat report and map will then be produced to create a detailed picture of the environment and its behaviour.
Rob Dewar, nature conservation advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how each species uses them.
This information will determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as the creation of grasslands and how forests should be maintained for bats and other associated species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK have declined considerably in the last century.
They are under threat from construction and development affecting their nests and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and electrical wiring can also pose a risk to them, as can insecticidal papers and other chemical treatments of building materials or attacks from domestic cats.
Bats aren't really blind,
But because of their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes in achieving their goal.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique that locates ants and obstacles in their flight path.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 major gardens and 76,000 hectares of land across the country, takes the bat issue very seriously.
It has ten trained experts in the field, who regularly conduct surveys, nest inspections, and sometimes rescues.
The organisation has even opened Scotland’s first and only dedicated bat reserve in the state of Threeve in Dumfries and Galloway, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
Property manager David Thompson says it’s the ideal territory for them.
“Here, in Threave, we have a fantastic area for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, lots of veteran trees and all the right habitat.
However, there’s still a lot unknown about bats, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to develop.”
It emphasizes the importance of checking for bats before carrying out maintenance tasks within the properties, since a breeding colony can be unintentionally destroyed and 400 females and offspring could be killed, which would mean annihilating an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, harass or molest them, as well as destroy their colonies.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish officer in charge of the Bat Conservation Trust, has encouraged the public to collaborate.
He said: “We still have a lot to learn about bats and many other species that we don’t know how their populations evolve.”
