US-China trade war could benefit Beijing
The first salvos of the U.S.-China trade war were deafening, and while the battle is far from over, a break between the countries could benefit Beijing, experts say.
U.S. President Donald Trump issued the first warning earlier this year by slapping tariffs on major Chinese exports such as solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The most significant escalation took place this week with new tariffs affecting $200 billion ($150 billion) in goods, taxing half of the goods entering the United States from China.
On all occasions, Beijing has retaliated by imposing tariffs of five to ten percent on US goods worth $60 billion.
China has pledged to match U.S. attacks, and the world’s second-most powerful economy is unlikely to loosen anytime soon.
Getting Washington to back down would mean bowing to demands, but publicly submitting to the United States would be too embarrassing for Chinese President Xi Jinping.
Still, experts say that if Beijing plays its cards right, the pressures of the U.S. trade war could positively help China in the long run by reducing the interdependence between the two economies.
“The fact that a quick policy decision in Washington or Beijing can set the stage for a plummeting economy in either country is actually far more dangerous than viewers have recognized so far,” said Abigail Grace, Asia-focused research associate at the Center for New American Security.
Syria ready for refugees to return, says foreign minister
Syria says it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and calls for help to rebuild a country devastated by a war that has been raging for more than seven years.
In a speech before the United Nations General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Moualem said the country’s conditions were improving.
“The situation on the ground today is more stable and secure thanks to the progress that has been made in the fight against terrorism,” he said.
The government continues to rehabilitate areas destroyed by terrorists to try to restore normalcy.
All the conditions for the voluntary return to the country of refugees who had to leave due to terrorism and unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods are already in place.
The UN estimates that, since the war began in 2011, more than 5.5 million Syrians have fled the country.
There are another six million people still living in the country who are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Moualem acknowledged that the Syrian regime would welcome help in rebuilding the devastated country.
But he also stressed that he would not accept conditional aid or aid from countries that promoted the insurgency.
Europe wins the Ryder Cup in Paris
The European team has won the 2018 Ryder Cup by defeating the North American team with a final score of 16.5 to 10.5 at Le Golf National, just outside Paris (France).
The U.S. now has six straight losses on European soil since it last won a Ryder Cup in Europe in 1993.
Europe regained the crown when Danish captain Thomas Bjorn's team scored the 14.5 points needed to beat the United States.
The American star Phil Mickelson, who had to fight for most of the tournament, threw his point of exit to the water in the hole 16 par 3, thus admitting his defeat to Francesco Molinari.
Italian golfer Molinari excelled in all his rounds, becoming one of only four players to ever score a 5-0-0 since the tournament’s current format began in 1979.
The American Jordan Spieth was defeated 5 and 4 against the player with the lowest classification of the European team, the Danish Thorbjorn Olesen.
World number one Dustin Johnson fell 2-1 to Englishman Ian Poulter, who could have played his last Ryder Cup.
Sergio Garcia, a veteran who already has eight Ryder Cups, became the European with the most victories of the tournament of all time, with 25.5 points in his career.
“I don’t usually cry, but I can’t help it today.
It's been a tough year.
I am totally grateful to Thomas for choosing me and believing in me.
I'm very, very happy that I was able to get the cup back.
It is an achievement for the whole team and I am very happy to have been able to help," said an excited Garcia after the victory of the European team.
Now he passes the torch to his compatriot John Rahm, who already defeated the American golf legend Tiger Woods by 2 and 1 in a singles match on Sunday.
“I’m incredibly proud to have beaten Tiger Woods, as I’ve grown up watching this man,” said 23-year-old golfer John Rahm.
Woods lost all four games in France and now has a 13-21-3 record in his Ryder Cup career.
This is a strange statistic for one of the greatest players of all time, who has won 14 major titles, trailing only Jack Nicklaus.
The American team had to fight all weekend to find the streets, with the exception of Patrick Reed, Justin Thomas and Tony Finau, who played a high-level golf throughout the tournament.
U.S. captain Jim Furyk spoke after his team's disappointing performance: "I'm very proud of these guys, they've never stopped fighting.
There was a moment this morning when we warmed up the situation in Europe.
But we spoiled it.
I want to congratulate Thomas.
He's a great captain.
All 12 players have played a very good game.
We will regroup, meet with the PGA of America and our Ryder Cup Committee, and move forward.
I love these 12 guys very much and I am proud to be their captain.
Now it's our turn to bow our heads.
They have overtaken us.”
Red Tide Update: Concentrations Decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The new report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall reduction in red tide concentrations in areas of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, irregular flowering conditions are being reported in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a reduction in concentrations.
Red tide bloom extends approximately along 130 miles of coastline from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Irregular plots can be found about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer places compared to last week.
Red tide has also been detected in Pasco County.
During the past week, average concentrations have been reported in Pinellas County and its coast, low-to-high concentrations in the Hillsborough County coast, background-to-high concentrations in Manatee County, background-to-high concentrations in Sarasota County and its coast, background-to-medium concentrations in Charlotte County, background-to-high concentrations in Lee County and its coast, and low concentrations in Collier County.
Respiratory irritation problems continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
No respiratory irritation problems have been reported in northwest Florida over the past week.
